1 (2) THIS SECTION DOES NOT INCREASE THE DUTY OF CARE FOR THE
2 ADMINISTRATION OR ANOTHER STATE AGENCY OR THEIR EMPLOYEES,
3 CONTRACTORS, OR CONTRACTOR’S EMPLOYEES FOR ANY TORT OR OTHER LIABILITY
4 PURPOSES IN CONNECTION WITH ACTIONS BY A PERSON ALLEGED TO HAVE
5 COMMITTED AN ASSAULT ON A PUBLIC TRANSIT OPERATOR OR PASSENGER.
6 (1) AT LEAST 30 DAYS, FOR A FIRST ACT OF ASSAULT OR
7 INTENTIONAL ACT CAUSING BODILY INJURY;
8 (2) AT LEAST 180 DAYS, FOR A SECOND ACT OF ASSAULT OR
9 INTENTIONAL ACT CAUSING BODILY INJURY; AND
10 (3) THE REMAINDER OF THE PERSON’S LIFE:
11 (I) FOR A THIRD ACT OF ASSAULT OR INTENTIONAL ACT
12 CAUSING BODILY INJURY; OR
13 (II) FOR ANY ACT OF ASSAULT OR INTENTIONAL ACT CAUSING
14 BODILY INJURY FOR WHICH THE PERSON USED A WEAPON.
15 (C) THE SECRETARY OR THE SECRETARY’S DESIGNEE MAY REDUCE OR
16 INCREASE THE PERIOD OF TIME THAT A PERSON WHO VIOLATES SUBSECTION (B) OF
17 THIS SECTION IS PROHIBITED FROM BOARDING A STATE PUBLIC TRANSIT SERVICE
18 OR ENTERING A STATE PUBLIC TRANSIT SERVICE STATION.
19 (D) (1) A PERSON WHO VIOLATES THIS SECTION IS SUBJECT TO
20 PROSECUTION FOR TRESPASSING.
21 (2) NOTHING IN THIS SECTION MAY BE CONSTRUED TO LIMIT OR
22 PROHIBIT THE ENFORCEMENT OF ANY OTHER STATE LAW.
23 (E) THE SECRETARY SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY OUT THIS
24 SECTION.
25 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
26 (a) On or before June 1, 2025, the Maryland Transit Administration, in
27 consultation with the Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority, the Joint Safety
28 Committee, and operator union representatives, shall convene a workgroup to create a rider
29 code of conduct and implement a comprehensive internal safety program to strengthen
30 protections for Administration operators and passengers through clear safety protocols,
31 strengthened safety policies, and improved risk mitigation measures.
32 (b) The workgroup:

4 SENATE BILL 858
1 (1) shall address consequences for violations in Administration facilities
2 that shall include ridership bans for an assault on a public transit operator or passenger as
3 soon as practicable, the possibility of legal action, and an appeals process;
4 (2) may not require a criminal conviction as a prerequisite to a ban on
5 public transit service usage; and
6 (3) shall authorize, under standards set by the workgroup, the use of public
7 transit facilities by a person accused of assault on a public transit operator or passenger, if
8 the assault was directly related to the person’s disability and the person is accompanied by
9 a direct support professional or another appropriate caregiver when using public transit
10 facilities.
11 (c) On or before October 1, 2025, the workgroup shall report its findings and
12 recommendations to the Maryland Transit Administrator and, in accordance with § 2–1257
13 of the State Government Article, the Senate Finance Committee and the House
14 Environment and Transportation Committee.
15 (d) After issuing the report under subsection (c) of this section, the workgroup
16 shall continue to assess the effectiveness of the proposed code of conduct and internal safety
17 program and recommend ongoing improvements.
18 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
19 (1) if the Maryland Transit Administration adopts a rider code of conduct
20 and implements a comprehensive internal safety program, with no further action required
21 by the General Assembly, Section 1 of this Act shall be abrogated and of no further force
22 and effect; and
23 (2) the Maryland Transit Administration shall notify the Department of
24 Legislative Services within 5 days after adoption of the rider code of conduct and
25 implementation of a comprehensive internal safety program as described in Section 2 of
26 this Act.
27 SECTION 2. 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
28 October June 1, 2025.

